Context
- We are currently running Phase 5 and Phase 6 verification for the Parallel scheduling engine.
- Phase 0–4 logic has already been validated and must remain unchanged.
- Important: This phase is NOT about redesigning the algorithm. It is only about verifying timezone conversion stability and fairness behavior under edge cases.

Scope of investigation
Allowed:
- Timezone conversion
- DST boundary handling
- Local time rendering
- Anchor time → week date conversion
- Non-integer UTC offsets (e.g. +05:30, +05:45)

Not allowed:
- Changing fairness scoring
- Changing rotation algorithm
- Changing feasibility logic
- Changing hard boundary enforcement
- Changing burden scoring rules
- Changing beam search or candidate ranking

Algorithm stability requirement
The following modules are considered LOCKED:

- rotation scoring
- fairness spread calculation
- consecutive burden limit logic
- feasibility detection
- hard boundary exclusion

If a bug appears during Phase 5/6 testing,
the fix must be limited strictly to:

timezone conversion or display logic.

DST rule
The system must produce consistent results when the meeting week occurs after a DST transition.

All base time selections (9 AM, 12 PM, 6 PM, etc.) must follow the SAME conversion rule between:

anchor timezone offset
and
actual meeting week local timezone offset.

No special-case behavior per hour is allowed.

Determinism requirement
Given the same inputs:
- team members
- timezones
- base time
- rotation length

The generated schedule must remain deterministic.

Testing priority
1. Non-integer timezone offsets (India, Nepal)
2. DST transition weeks (US and Europe)
3. Cross-day labeling
4. Rotation fairness behavior
